Report Notebook¶

This Notebook covers two of the requested reports:

  • A report on the retention and use of the moodtracker feature.
  • A report on the employee emotional state and evolution per industry.
  • A report on content consumption.

Since the information necessary for all the reports is shared, it was decided that all three would share the same notebook, so that they can share the same functions, variables and transformations.

Given that we have 100k registers (rows) in the moodtracker table, we can see that around 1.65% of our registers have an empty value for the mood variable. At this point it is not clear wether this is due to incorrect data or the tool not being used, so we won't address it for now.

We can see in the plot above that the number of registers on the moodtracker table until 2020-01-22, where we can see an increase to a new level, that is sustained until 2020-01-27. During this interval the values are very consistent, as we can see by how tight the percentile range is, since the values for the 25%, 50% and 75% percentiles are very close to each other.

Following this we see a sharp dip on 2020-01-28, followed by a small increase the following day and another dip to the minimum value registered of 887, followed by another increase on the last day of the month.

The plots above shows for how long users used the moodtracker feature as well as how frequently they did it.

From the left plot we can see that most of the users used the moodtracker up to 19 to 27 days, with the median at 24 days and the mean close to 23 days. The 27 days limit is a curious one, since it lines up with the day where the big drop in moodtracker logs is registered (2020-01-28).

The right plot shows the time passed in hours between a user's consecutive logs. Here we can already see that there might be an issue on our table, since we have a minimum value of 0 hours, meaning that there are users with more than one log in the same instant of time. This is something we will get back to later.

We can observe with this plot that 50% of the users waits between 2 to 14 hours before returning to use the moodtracker. We can see how this data is affected by the drop in users towards the end of the month by looking at the mean (~8 hours) vs the median (~5 hours). Since the median is more resistent to outlier values, it's expected that if the sudden drops at the end of the month hadn't happened, then these values would be closer, meaning that on average our users wait around 5 hours before using the moodtracker feature again.

First & Last Seen ¶

Another interesting measure we can take is the number of users first seen on a given day and the number of last seen. This can also show us the first and last mood logged per user.

To make the plot above, the first and last day of the month were excluded, since we don't have visibility into the periods before and after this month, so we can't make any statement about the number of new/leaving users on those days. This is also relevant when discussing the "Last Seen" curve, since we don't know if users that may have "left" the moodtracker actually used it again on the following month.

Looking at the "First Seen" curve, we see that the amount of new users during the month decreased almost exponentially and from 2020-01-11 forwards, no new user was registered.

Regarding the "Last Seen" curve, we can see that up until 2020-01-23, there were no users stopping the usage of the moodtracker. This value only starts to increase significantly around 2020-01-26. We can see a local maxima at 2020-01-27 and the maximum value at 2020-01-29. These are the days that precede the big drops in the number of moodtracker logs.

In the plots above the y axis (Number of users) is share between both plots, to better compare the number of users. Also, just like before, the first and last day of the month were excluded.

We can see on the left-side plot, that most users first show up with a "angry" or "super-happy" mood, but as time goes on, there is more balance on the amount of each mood registered. On the right-side we can see an almost mirror progression, as the number of users "leaving" increases, so does the difference between the mood categories.

Similar to what've seen before, most of the users log 1 or 2 different kinds of mood in a given day. We can see that only 1 in 4 people register 3 or more distinct mood statuses in a day. It's important to make this distinction, since it will be crucial in how we go about analysing the mood of the users over time.

Like before, we have inconsistent number of logs, 82994 vs 100000. We aggregated our data by userid and date. If in the same day, the same user logged the same mood more than once, we are only counting it once (hence the importance of being explicit about distinct mood values).

Now that we have some insights regarding the use of the moodtracker, we can start to think about how to connect the information on moodtracker_df with the one of the population.

Emotional State Analysis ¶

Our target variable is mood. This is a categorical variable, meaning that we can't simply compute it's average value for each day, since all we have are strings.

  • Since we have some insight on the moodtracker data, we can transform our table to make our life easier while still using the data correctly. Here's what we know:
    • Most users don't use the moodtracker feature more than 2~3 times per day.
    • 80% of the users log either 1 or 2 distinct moods in a day.
    • A user can log the same mood more than once in a day.
  • With these informations in mind, we're going to edit our moodtracker table so that we only have 1 mood value per user per day. The steps to do this are:
    • Take the most frequent mood for each user, each day.
    • If there is no clear value that is more frequent than the others, take the last one registered.
  • This analysis will be biased towards the mood of people at the end of the day.

General Population ¶

From the plot above we can see the extreme moods ('super-happy' and 'angry') are the most common moods reported.

'Sad' and 'Ok' mood follow, not being represented every day, but with significant expression in some cases. It seems like whenever there is an increase in the amount of users registering either 'angry' or 'super-happy' moods is at the cost of these moods, since they are reduced and sometimes even supressed fairly regularly.

Curiously the 'happy' mood is very rare, even more than the unknow (in the legend colored blue).

Since 'super-happy' and 'angry' dwarf the remaining mood statuses, we're going to drill down further in those.

We can see that the number of users that keep either mood status from one day to another is stable. An increase in either mood does not reflect in a decrease in the opposite one, as noted previously. Like mentioned before, the drop in the final days of the month are proportional for these moods.

Now that we've seen the picture for the total population, we can drill down on different subsets. For that we will finally integrate the pop_df table. We are going to look into the following subsets:

  • All users that work in each industry
  • All users that work in each company
  • All users of a given (guessed) gender - only considering male or female here
  • All users of a given age range - 3 groups: <= 21 years old | > 21 & < 32 years old | >= 32 years old (these groups were decided based on the quantiles of the age of the total users)

The results will be discussed at the end.

Note: Since the '' (unknown) mood does not add a lot of information when we reduce our population size, so for these subset analysis we are going to discard those entries.

Content Consumption ¶

In this section we will go over the content consumption, and see how it relates to the users and it's evolution during the month under analysis.

We can see in this plot that content access and display seem to be positively correlated, with content access following a similar trend to content displayer, albeit with less abrupt increases, resulting in a smoother curve. Just like in the previous report, there is a significant drop of content displayed and accessed on 2020-01-28 and on 2020-01-30.

To further understand the relationship between these two variables, it could be interesting to investigate the overlap between content displayed to an user and the content the user actually accesses.

First rows of the grouped table
Out[39]:
userid event_date contentid unique nunique
0 00038938-418a-4c53-8dc8-3cac021942cf 2020-01-01 20 access 1
1 00038938-418a-4c53-8dc8-3cac021942cf 2020-01-01 54 access 1
2 00038938-418a-4c53-8dc8-3cac021942cf 2020-01-01 67 display 1
3 00038938-418a-4c53-8dc8-3cac021942cf 2020-01-01 76 display | access 2
4 00038938-418a-4c53-8dc8-3cac021942cf 2020-01-01 93 display 1

We can now check 3 groups of contents:

  • Contents displayed to an user and accessed the same day
  • Contents displayed to an user and not accessed the same day
  • Contents accessed by an user without being displayed on the same day.

The previous plots show us the interaction between a content being displayed and accessed by the same user on the same day.

  • It is clear that some contents are more pushed towards the users than others, as seen in the cases where the "only displayed" bar of certain contents is larger than the complete bar of others. These contents have a smaller probability of being accessed without being displayed to the user, and thus have to be pushed harder towards the user.
  • The other group of contents is more accessed without being displayed than simply being displayed, suggesting users are more proactive in accessing these contents.
  • Only a small fraction of contents are displayed to the user and accessed on the same day. This can mean several things:
    • Users are already aware of which contents they want to consume or not, thus the large values of "Only accessed" for some contents.
    • Users access contents that are displayed to them early on, but as time goes on, they are able to access the contents they care about without them being displayed to them.

Closing remarks ¶

In this report we:

  • Described the population;
  • Explored the moodtracker data, studied it's use over time and how users use it.
  • Described and compared the emotional state and its evolution of different groups within our population.
  • Analysed the content comsumption.

The main learnings are:

  • We learned that the population can be grouped in different ways, with slightly different results depending on the criteria. A further study on this subject with a larger dataset could help further define and refine the groups.
  • We were able to find some pattern when it comes to the usage of the moodtracker feature, that could potentially be used to tweak the tool itself.
  • We found that the general drop in content consumption registered at the end of the month also occured in the use of the moodtracker feature.
    • We identified a drop in the number of users, however it cannot be definitively stated that this was the reason for the drop, since we don't have visibility into the following week or month.
    • We saw that both the amount of content displayed/accessed also suffered a drop in the same day.

The table above shows us that the period of time between 3 and 11 AM are most likely to have few users, even on what seem to be "regular" days, such as 2020-01-23. On the remainder hours we often find 2020-01-28, the day with the largest drop in user interaction.

We will look into these days as our baselines, and compare them with the days that surround 2020-01-28 and 2020-01-30 (2020-01-27, 2020-01-29 and 2020-01-31).

We are going to split our comparisons in 3 intervals:

  • 0:00 to 2:00
  • 3:00 to 11:00
  • 12:00 to 23:00

Here we finally see the biggest difference between what happens on 2020-01-28, 2020-01-30 and the other days. The number of users we see for each hour is several times smaller on the 28th than on the other days, that actually present very similar values amongst themselves. On the case of 2020-01-30 there aren't even registers.

Recall that on the first interval table we saw that the first hours of the 29th also showed some weird values in the first hours of the day - the hours following the end of the 28th.

In summary, given:

  • The abnormal decrease of hourly users starts at 12:00 on the 28th and continues into the first hours of the 29th.
  • The lack of registers for the 30th after 2:00 that continues until 12:00 on the 31st.
  • The fact that on the 31st the values for the third period (the one that registers the most usage of the moodtracker) are back to normal.
  • The fact that the same drop in usage is registered the displayed and accessed contents.

Leads me to believe that the possible explanation for this is some technical problem on the website or some deployment and not a loss of users.

The small number of registers on the third interval for the 28th suggests that the website was working, however only a limited amount of users could use it (it could be either a technical problem or a reduced number of users testing something).

The complete absence of registers for the 30th during the interval strongly hints that the moodtracker tool was unacessible. Another possibility for this day is that something happened with the database and nothing was written to it on this period, but given the precendent of what happened on the 28th I find that unlikely.
